                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout><q>Parts of the roman and much of the ogam inscriptions have been lost... Missing and fragmentary letters have been reconstructed from Morgan's drawing (Illus. CM25.2)... A roman-letter, Latin inscription deeply <rs type="execution" key="incised" ref="https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/1.html">incised</rs> in two lines reading vertically downwards... [A] fragmentary ogam inscription is deeply incised up the right angle (A/D) of the face. There may also be traces of possible ogam strokes on the top left corner of a... The surviving parts of the ogam inscription are placed to the right o the roman inscription, rather than to the left, as is more usual, and possibly continued round the top of the monument. Although Morgan's drawing of the roman-letter inscription appears accurate, his record of the ogam inscription seems unreliable. The monument was probably already damaged... and ogam inscriptions were not understood at this time.</q><bibl><ptr target ="#EDW2007"/><citedRange unit="page">251-252</citedRange></bibl></layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote><q>The inscription is in capitals, with a space between the two words in line 2. The B's have separate loops; R's have a separate diagonal which is almost horizontal, that in line 2 has an open loop. In line 1 the horizontal of the L slopes downwards; the strokes of the M are widely spaced. In line 2 F is cursive; S is geometric and shown as a Greek sigma; G is sickle-shaped; the final I is horizontal.</q><bibl><ptr target ="#EDW2007"/><citedRange unit="page">251-252</citedRange></bibl><height></height>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
